Part I - Loan Data from Prosper¶

by Mustapha Aminu Saleh¶

Introduction¶

The dataset contain information on 113,937 loans with each loan having 81 variables, including loan amount, borrower/interest rate, current loan status, borrower income and others. The goal of this analysis is to assess the possible reasons for not completing loan repayment

In [22]:
#Create a dictionary with each number corresponding to the reason
listing_cat = {0:"Not Available", 1:"Debt Consolidation", 2:"Home Improvement", 3:"Business", 4:"Personal Loans",
          5:"Student Use", 6:"Auto", 7:"Other", 8:"Baby and Adoption", 9:"Boat", 10:"Cosmetic Procedure",
          11:"Engagement Ring", 12:"Green Loans", 13:"Household Expenses", 14:"Large Purchases", 15:"Medical/Dental",
          16:"Motorcycle", 17:"RV", 18:"Taxes", 19:"Vacation", 20:"Wedding Loans"}
In [23]:
# make a function to change the numbers to the corresponding reason
def listing(loan):
    if loan["ListingCategory (numeric)"] in listing_cat.keys():
        category = listing_cat[loan["ListingCategory (numeric)"]]
        return category
    else:
        return loan["ListingCategory (numeric)"]
In [24]:
#apply the function
df["ListingCategory (numeric)"] = df.apply(listing, axis=1)
